ogynous ideal of the modern woman's movement. In exploring the many aspects of his subject, Brown compares Shelley with his contemporaries, particularly Byron, and draws upon extensive research into the laws, ideas, and practices of the period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEnglische Literatur. 0aErotik (Motiv). 0aFeminism in literature. 0aFrauenbewegung. 0aFéminisme dans la littérature. 0aLiteratur. 0aSex in literature. 0aSexualität. 0aSexualité dans la littérature. 4aFeminism in literature. 4aLITERARY CRITICISM / General. 4aPSYCHOLOGY / Human Sexuality. 4aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory. 4aShelley, Percy Bysshe, 1792-1822 -- Criticism and interpretation. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Literature eBook Packagez9783110353501oZDB-23-HLI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067473184440uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067473185140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674731851423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674731851.jpg  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-HCO  aZDB-23-HLI